      <h3>Planes of Motion, <em>Joint Actions &amp; Axes</em></h3>
      <table class="ref-table">
        <tr><th>Plane</th><th>Divides body</th><th>Joint motions</th><th>Axis of rotation</th><th>Examples</th></tr>
        <tr><td><strong style="color:var(--blue)">Sagittal</strong></td><td>Right &amp; left halves</td><td>Flexion / extension (ankle: dorsiflexion / plantarflexion)</td><td>Frontal (coronal) axis</td><td>Biceps curls, squats, walking, stair climbing</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong style="color:var(--orange)">Frontal</strong></td><td>Front &amp; back halves</td><td>Abduction / adduction, lateral flexion, eversion / inversion</td><td>Anterior-posterior axis</td><td>Lateral raises, side lunges, side shuffles</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong style="color:var(--teal)">Transverse</strong></td><td>Upper &amp; lower halves</td><td>Internal / external rotation, L/R spinal rotation, pronation / supination</td><td>Longitudinal (vertical) axis</td><td>Cable rotations, throwing, swinging a bat</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="ref-card">
      <h3>The Three <em>Muscle Actions</em></h3>
      <div class="key-term"><strong>Concentric — isolated function</strong><span>Muscle <strong style="color:var(--text)">shortens</strong> and <strong style="color:var(--text)">accelerates</strong> a movement (e.g., lifting phase of a curl).</span></div>
      <div class="key-term"><strong>Eccentric — integrated function</strong><span>Muscle <strong style="color:var(--text)">lengthens</strong> under load and <strong style="color:var(--text)">decelerates</strong> a movement; absorbs force (e.g., lowering phase).</span></div>
      <div class="key-term"><strong>Isometric — integrated function</strong><span>Muscle produces force with <strong style="color:var(--text)">no change in length</strong> and <strong style="color:var(--text)">stabilizes</strong> a joint (e.g., plank).</span></div>
    </div>

    <div class="ref-card">
      <h3>The Four <em>Muscle Roles</em></h3>
      <table class="ref-table">
        <tr><th>Role</th><th>What it does</th></tr>
        <tr><td><strong style="color:var(--accent)">Agonist</strong></td><td>Prime mover — drives the motion</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong style="color:var(--blue)">Antagonist</strong></td><td>Directly opposes the prime mover</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong style="color:var(--teal)">Synergist</strong></td><td>Assists the prime mover</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong style="color:var(--warn)">Stabilizer</strong></td><td>Supports/holds while movers work</td></tr>
      </table>
      <div class="key-term" style="margin-top:10px"><strong>Hip extension example</strong><span>Agonist: gluteus maximus · Antagonist: psoas · Synergist: hamstrings · Stabilizer: deep core (TVA, multifidus)</span></div>
    </div>

    <div class="ref-card">
      <h3>Pronation vs <em>Supination</em></h3>
      <table class="ref-table">
        <tr><th>Pronation (loading)</th><th>Supination (push-off)</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Eccentric — decelerates</td><td>Concentric — produces force</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Tibia/femur internal rotation</td><td>Tibia/femur external rotation</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Foot/ankle: dorsiflex, evert, abduct</td><td>Foot/ankle: plantarflex, invert, adduct</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Knee/hip: flex, adduct, IR</td><td>Knee/hip: extend, abduct, ER</td></tr>
      </table>
      <div class="key-term" style="margin-top:10px"><strong>Tri-planar</strong><span>Both are multiplanar, synchronized motions occurring in all three planes at once.</span></div>
    </div>

    <div class="ref-card">
      <h3>Mechanics — <em>Length-Tension, Couples, Levers</em></h3>
      <div class="key-term"><strong>Length-tension</strong><span>A muscle produces its greatest force at its <strong style="color:var(--text)">optimal (resting) length</strong>. Chronically lengthened or shortened muscles lose force.</span></div>
      <div class="key-term"><strong>Force-couple</strong><span>Two+ muscles pulling in different directions to rotate a joint. Scapular upward rotation = upper trap + lower trap + serratus anterior.</span></div>
      <div class="key-term"><strong>Levers</strong><span>Bones = levers · joints = fulcrums · muscles = force · body part/weight = resistance. <strong style="color:var(--text)">3 lever classes.</strong> Torque = force × distance from fulcrum.</span></div>
    </div>

